Claims WHAT IS CLAIMED IS: 1. A computer implemented method comprising: receiving a write request to a database, the write request specifying an original table (OT) name of one of a plurality of tables in the database, a column name of one of a plurality of columns in the OT, and a data entry to be written; accessing an OT primary key where the data entry is to be written; writing the data entry to a first location in the OT corresponding to the column name and the OT primary key; preparing an additional authenticated data (AAD) comprising the OT name, the column name, and the OT primary key; obtaining a cipher text based on the data entry and the AAD; and writing the cipher text to a second location in a cipher text column of an encrypted table (ET) different than the OT, the second location being in a row of the ET where the row also stores the OT name, the column name, and the OT primary key. 2. The computer implemented method of claim 1, wherein the write request further comprises the OT primary key, and accessing the primary key of the original table comprises: extracting the OT primary key from the write request. 3. The computer implemented method of claim 1, wherein accessing the primary key of the original table comprises: initiating a transaction state with the database creating a new primary key in the original table and preventing the new primary key from being used outside of the transaction; responsive to the data entry being written to the first location and the cipher text being written to the second location, exiting the transaction state, thereby allowing free use of the new primary key. 4. The computer implemented method of claim 1, wherein obtaining the cipher text comprises: communicating the data entry, the AAD, and an identification of a cryptographic key to a cryptography service; and 

 responsive to the communication, receiving a cipher text from the cryptography service. 5. The computer implemented method of claim 1, wherein the AAD further comprises additional information stored in the database but not in the encrypted table. 6. The computer implemented method of claim 1, further comprising: accessing the row of the ET corresponding to the OT primary key; creating a second AAD based on at least some of the contents of the row other than the cipher text; communicating the cipher text and the second AAD to a cryptography service; responsive to the cryptography service returning the data entry, validating the encryption as successful; and responsive to the cryptography service returning a decryption error, reporting that the encryption was unsuccessful or that a write attack has occurred. 7. The computer implemented method of claim 1, further comprising: deleting the data entry from the original table. 8. The computer implemented method of claim 1, wherein writing the cipher text to the second location further comprises: writing the original table name to an original table column in the row of the ET; writing the column name to a column column in the row of the ET; and writing the OT primary key to an OT primary key column in the row of the ET. 9. The computer implemented method of claim 1, wherein writing the cipher text to the second location further comprises: writing to a key revision column at least one of an identifier for the cryptographic key and an identifier of a generation of a cryptographic key. 10. A computer implemented method comprising: receiving a write request to a database, the write request including an original table name of one of a plurality of tables in the database, a column name of one of a plurality of columns in the original table, and a data entry to be written; accessing an original table (OT) primary key; 

 preparing an additional authenticated data (AAD) comprising the OT name, the column name, and the OT primary key; obtaining a cipher text based on the data entry and the AAD; and writing the cipher text to a location in a cipher text column of an encrypted table (ET) different than the OT, the second location being in a row of the ET where the row also stores the OT name, the column name, and the OT primary key, and wherein the data entry is not written to the OT. 11. A computer implemented method comprising: receiving a read request to a database, the read request including an original table (OT) name of one of a plurality of tables in the database, a column name of one of a plurality of columns in the OT; accessing an OT primary key where the data entry is to be read from; reading a data entry from a first location in the OT corresponding to the column name and the OT primary key; reading a cipher text from a first location in a cipher text column of an encrypted table (ET) different than the OT, the second location being in a row of the ET where the row also stores the OT name, the column name, and the OT primary key; preparing, as read from the ET, an additional authenticated data (AAD) comprising the OT name, the column name, and the OT primary key; sending a decryption request to a cryptographic service, the request comprising the cipher text and the AAD; responsive to receiving a response that the decryption was successful, receiving a plaintext version of the cipher text and validating the encryption as successful if the plaintext version of the cipher text matches the data entry accessed from the OT.
